CDC publish allergy guidelines for schools
On Wednesday, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), a set of guidelines for dealing with food allergies for children in schools.
These are the first such directives issued by the US, as the number of school children with food allergies.
One in 20 children in the United States now has a food allergy.
The prevalence of food allergies among children has increased by 18 percent between 1997 and 2007, according to the CDC.
The guidelines provide information for schools, the faculty and staff to raise awareness of food allergies and how to deal with children who are allergic reactions.
It is also recommended that schools Epinephrin stock - the auto-injection of the brand EpiPen is most commonly used in order to deal with a potentially fatal hypersensitivity reaction.
The legislators in the federal states have recently changed the rules so that schools can keep Epinephrin easier.
The report also includes a list of typical symptoms that are called by children who have an allergic reaction.
Children may say: "It feels as if something is on my tongue," "my tongue feels as if a hair on my tongue," or "tickles."
